Question 2.1: (2 pts)

Using the ggplot2 package, create a simple scatterplot showing chick weight (y-axis) as a function of Time. This time, relabel the axes more informatively and give the plot a title.
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data = ChickWeight, mapping = aes(Time, weight)) +
    geom_point(size = 1) + ggtitle("Weight of Chick Based on Time") +
    ylab("Weight (g)") + xlab("Time (hours)")

Question 2.2: (3 pts)

Building upon the previous plot, map Chick to an aesthetic that assigns a color to each chicks data points. Add lines that connect each chicks points together. Finally, remove the legend.
ggplot(data = ChickWeight, mapping = aes(Time, weight,
    color = Chick)) + geom_point(size = 1) + ggtitle("Weight of Chick Based on Time") +
    ylab("Weight (g)") + xlab("Time (hours)") + geom_line(aes(group = Chick),
    size = 0.4) + theme(legend.position = "none")

Question 2.3: (2 pts)

Take the plot you made in Question 3 and remove the color from the points only (leave the lines colored by chick, but make all of the points white). Put the points on top of the lines.
ggplot(data = ChickWeight, mapping = aes(Time, weight,
    color = Chick)) + geom_line(aes(group = Chick),
    size = 0.4) + geom_point(size = 1, color = "white") +
    ggtitle("Weight of Chick Based on Time") + ylab("Weight (g)") +
    xlab("Time (hours)") + theme(legend.position = "none")

Question 3.1: (2 pts)

A scatterplot might not be the best way to visualize this data: It calls attention to the relationship between weight and time, but it can be hard to see the differences between diets. A more traditional approach for achieving this list desideratum would be to a barplot of group means with standard error bars showing +/- 1 standard error.
Create a plot using geom_bar where each bars height corresponds to the average chick weight for each of the four diet conditions. Rename the y-axis to include units (e.g., with scale_y_continuous(name=), with ylab(), with labs()) and make the major tick marks go from 0 to 150 by 25 (with breaks=).
ggplot(data = ChickWeight, mapping = aes(x = Diet)) +
    geom_bar(aes(y = weight), stat = "summary", fun = mean) +
    ylab("Weight of chicks (g)") + scale_y_continuous(name = "Weight of chicks (g)",
    breaks = seq(0, 150, 25))

3.2 (3 pts)

Add error bars showing \(\pm 1\ SE\) using geom_errorbar(stat="summary"). Make the error-bars skinnier by adding a width= argument. Color the bars (not the error bars, but the bar chart bars) by diet and change from the default color scheme using a scale_fill_ or a scale_color_
ggplot(data = ChickWeight, mapping = aes(x = Diet,
    y = weight, fill = Diet)) + geom_bar(aes(y = weight),
    stat = "summary", show.legend = FALSE) + geom_errorbar(stat = "summary",
    width = 0.5) + ylab("Weight of chicks (g)") + scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0,
    150, 25)) + scale_fill_manual(values = c(`1` = "#E0BBE4",
    `2` = "#957DAD", `3` = "#D291BC", `4` = "#FEC8D8"))

3.3 (2 pts)

Take your code from 3.2 and replace geom_bar() with geom_point. Remove the breaks= argument from scale_y_continuous. Make the points larger and color them all red. Put them on top of the error bars.
ggplot(data = ChickWeight, mapping = aes(x = Diet,
    y = weight, fill = Diet)) + geom_errorbar(stat = "summary",
    width = 0.5) + geom_point(aes(y = weight), stat = "summary",
    color = "red", size = 4, show.legend = FALSE) +
    ylab("Weight of chicks (g)") + scale_y_continuous()
